  <!-- CHAPTER 6,  THE YEAR OF SILENCE -->

  <section id="le-silence" class="py-24 lg:py-32 bg-white">
    <div class="max-w-[680px] mx-auto px-10 sm:px-16 lg:px-24">
      <span class="block text-xs font-light tracking-[0.2em] uppercase text-[#8B7A3A] mb-6">Chapter 6</span>
      <h2 class="font-playfair text-3xl md:text-4xl lg:text-5xl font-medium text-[#2C2824] mb-12 tracking-tight leading-tight">
        The Year of Silence
      </h2>

      <p class="text-lg md:text-xl font-light text-[#2C2824]/85 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        January 2024. Grand Shambala has been weathertight for three weeks. We go in. It's vast. It's cold. The straw bales are visible, raw. Two 350 m² floors, one above the other, empty. The wind whistles through the gaps the render hasn't yet closed. The building waits.
      </p>
      <p class="text-lg md:text-xl font-light text-[#2C2824]/85 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        2024 is the year when almost nothing gets built at Grand Shambala. It's the year we look for partners, refine the vision, work on the business model. How does Grand Shambala fit into LAOM? What are the uses? How do we want to live inside?
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-10 sm:px-16 lg:px-24 my-12">
      <img src="/images/laom/grand-shambala/grand-shambala-paille-brute-hiver-2024.webp" alt="Grand Shambala raw in 2024, exposed straw, grey winter sky, the year of silence" title="The building waiting through 2024" class="w-full aspect-[21/9] object-cover rounded-sm" loading="lazy" decoding="async" />
    </div>

    <div class="max-w-[680px] mx-auto px-10 sm:px-16 lg:px-24">
      <p class="text-lg md:text-xl font-light text-[#2C2824]/85 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        The original plan called for three partners. But there weren't enough people. The project needs new partners to come alive. And partners aren't invented—you wait for them. You find them. It takes time.
      </p>
      <p class="text-lg md:text-xl font-light text-[#2C2824]/85 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        It's also the year Charly understands something essential: he won't live in Grand Shambala. His home will be Petit Shambala, on the other side of the path. He'll keep a small studio in Grand Shambala, but the building won't be his. The founder stepping back so the project can move forward.
      </p>
      <p class="text-lg md:text-xl font-light text-[#2C2824]/85 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        Then, at the end of 2024, a ritual gesture. Fifteen people. Fifteen days. Sixty square metres of earth render applied by hand to the inner walls. It's tiny next to the 850 m² total. But it's not a build. It's a ceremony. We touch the building. We tell it: we didn't forget you.
      </p>

      <blockquote class="my-12 py-8 border-l-2 border-[#C4A855] pl-8">
        <p class="text-xl md:text-2xl font-light italic text-[#2C2824]/85 leading-relaxed">
          Grand Shambala was dreamed by a man who ended up understanding it would not belong to him.
        </p>
      </blockquote>

      <p class="text-lg md:text-xl font-light text-[#2C2824]/85 leading-relaxed">
        The new partners arrive at the end of 2024 and start of 2025. The building will finally know who it's for.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>


  <!-- CHAPTER 7,  THE SKIN -->

  <section id="la-peau" class="py-24 lg:py-32 bg-[#FAF8F5]">
    <div class="max-w-[680px] mx-auto px-10 sm:px-16 lg:px-24">
      <span class="block text-xs font-light tracking-[0.2em] uppercase text-[#8B7A3A] mb-6">Chapter 7</span>
      <h2 class="font-playfair text-3xl md:text-4xl lg:text-5xl font-medium text-[#2C2824] mb-12 tracking-tight leading-tight">
        The Skin
      </h2>

      <p class="text-lg md:text-xl font-light text-[#2C2824]/85 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        2025 explodes. The new partners bring clarity. The programme crystallises. The lots take shape. And Grand Shambala, after a full year of silence, transforms at a pace that surprises even those who built it.
      </p>
      <p class="text-lg md:text-xl font-light text-[#2C2824]/85 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        The <strong>south façade</strong> is fully reworked; each partner now knows where their space will be. <strong>Windows are cut into the east and west gables</strong>, where there was only straw. Each opening is a deliberate act.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-10 sm:px-16 lg:px-24 mt-4 mb-12">
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <img src="/images/laom/grand-shambala/facade-sud-grand-shambala-ouvertures-2025.webp" alt="South façade of Grand Shambala reworked in 2025 with final openings" title="South facade after 2025 rework of openings" class="aspect-[4/3] w-full object-cover rounded-sm" loading="lazy" decoding="async" />
        <img src="/images/laom/grand-shambala/fenetres-pignons-est-ouest-grand-shambala.webp" alt="New windows cut into the east and west gables of Grand Shambala" title="Openings carved into the straw walls" class="aspect-[4/3] w-full object-cover rounded-sm" loading="lazy" decoding="async" />
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="max-w-[680px] mx-auto px-10 sm:px-16 lg:px-24">
      <p class="text-lg md:text-xl font-light text-[#2C2824]/85 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        Then comes the <strong>external lime render</strong>. We worked the colour with pigments from local earth, we made our own wash with soil from the site. The building receives its face. Raw straw disappears under a mineral, soft, pigmented skin. The metamorphosis is striking.
      </p>
      <p class="text-lg md:text-xl font-light text-[#2C2824]/85 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        What doesn't show in the photos is how long it took. Two and a half months. Four people. With the spray machine it was a constant battle: the hose blocked, dried lime caused blockages, everything had to be cleared. We had a scratch coat from 2023. In 2025 we did the base coat with anti-crack mesh, then the final coat by hand—trowel, sponge—and finally the wash. Erecting the scaffold, moving it, dismantling it, carrying the hose… It was very, very long. But worth it.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-10 sm:px-16 lg:px-24 mt-4 mb-12">
      <img src="/images/laom/grand-shambala/avant-apres-enduit-chaux-facade-grand-shambala.webp" alt="Before/after diptych, raw straw façade vs lime-rendered façade with local earth pigments" title="Facade transformation: before and after lime render" class="w-full aspect-[16/9] object-cover rounded-sm" loading="lazy" decoding="async" />
    </div>

    <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-10 sm:px-16 lg:px-24 mb-12">
      <img src="/images/laom/grand-shambala/application-enduit-chaux-murs-paille-grand-shambala.webp" alt="Applying lime render to the straw walls of Grand Shambala" title="Lime rendering in progress on site" class="w-full aspect-[16/9] object-cover rounded-sm" loading="lazy" decoding="async" />
    </div>

    <div class="max-w-[680px] mx-auto px-10 sm:px-16 lg:px-24">
      <p class="text-lg md:text-xl font-light text-[#2C2824]/85 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        The east and west roof gables are clad in wood. The <strong>LAOM sign in corten steel</strong> is fixed to the façade, the rust tone burning in the evening light. It's the first visible sign from the road. The building has a name.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-10 sm:px-16 lg:px-24 mt-4 mb-12">
      <img src="/images/laom/grand-shambala/enseigne-laom-acier-corten-facade.webp" alt="LAOM corten steel sign on the façade of Grand Shambala" title="The corten steel sign, first visible marker from the road" class="w-full aspect-[4/3] object-cover rounded-sm" loading="lazy" decoding="async" />
    </div>

    <div class="max-w-[680px] mx-auto px-10 sm:px-16 lg:px-24">
      <p class="text-lg md:text-xl font-light text-[#2C2824]/85 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        Under the tiles we insulate with <strong>blown loose chopped straw</strong> between the trusses. Here too it was an adventure. We used three different machines. We even tried to build our own—a chip-extraction motor bought for a joinery workshop, flexible hoses, €1,700 invested for nothing. The motor wasn't powerful enough, the hose created friction on the straw. Failure. We finally found an American machine that did the job.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-10 sm:px-16 lg:px-24 mt-4 mb-12">
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <img src="/images/laom/grand-shambala/isolation-paille-hachee-combles-grand-shambala.webp" alt="Blown chopped straw insulation between trusses in the loft of Grand Shambala" title="Chopped straw being blown into the loft" class="aspect-[4/3] w-full object-cover rounded-sm" loading="lazy" decoding="async" />
        <img src="/images/laom/grand-shambala/fenetre-mur-paille-paysage-aveyron.webp" alt="Window set into the straw wall, Aveyron landscape framed by the opening" title="The Aveyron landscape seen from inside Grand Shambala" class="aspect-[4/3] w-full object-cover rounded-sm" loading="lazy" decoding="async" />
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="max-w-[680px] mx-auto px-10 sm:px-16 lg:px-24">
      <p class="text-lg md:text-xl font-light text-[#2C2824]/85 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        Inside, <strong>earth render is sprayed by machine</strong>. The same earth-straw mix as in 2024, but this time not by hand. Three people, four days, hundreds of square metres covered. A year earlier, fifteen people had covered sixty square metres in fifteen days. The same gesture, the same material, efficiency multiplied twentyfold.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-10 sm:px-16 lg:px-24 mt-4 mb-12">
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <img src="/images/laom/grand-shambala/projection-enduit-terre-murs-interieurs-grand-shambala.webp" alt="Machine-sprayed earth render on the interior walls of Grand Shambala" title="Earth render sprayed mechanically inside" class="aspect-[4/3] w-full object-cover rounded-sm" loading="lazy" decoding="async" />
        <img src="/images/laom/grand-shambala/projection-enduit-terre-detail-finition.webp" alt="Machine-sprayed earth render, detail of the gesture and finish" title="Close-up of the earth render finish" class="aspect-[4/3] w-full object-cover rounded-sm" loading="lazy" decoding="async" />
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="max-w-[680px] mx-auto px-10 sm:px-16 lg:px-24">
      <blockquote class="my-12 py-8 border-l-2 border-[#C4A855] pl-8">
        <p class="text-xl md:text-2xl font-light italic text-[#2C2824]/85 leading-relaxed">
          The hand, in 2024, was love while waiting. The machine, in 2025, is the efficiency of a project that finally knows where it's going.
        </p>
      </blockquote>

      <p class="text-lg md:text-xl font-light text-[#2C2824]/85 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        The <strong>first-floor partitions</strong> start to go up. And here, the choice of walls alone tells the philosophy of the project.
      </p>
      <p class="text-lg md:text-xl font-light text-[#2C2824]/85 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        Three types of partition coexist in Grand Shambala. <strong>Timber-frame walls filled with earth-straw</strong>, heavy, dense, bringing thermal mass and acoustic insulation that plasterboard could never provide. <strong>Classic timber-frame partitions</strong>, insulated with wood fibre, for lighter separations. And <strong>37 cm straw-bale walls</strong>, used as internal partitions to separate the main lots—here it's no longer structure but pure insulation, an internal wall that breathes and regulates humidity without being asked.
      </p>
      <p class="text-lg md:text-xl font-light text-[#2C2824]/85 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        A material everyone underestimates, taken to a level no one imagined. That's the kind of paradox that sums up the whole of Grand Shambala.
      </p>
      <p class="text-lg md:text-xl font-light text-[#2C2824]/85 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        For the first time in two years you can walk through Grand Shambala and say: "Here will be the common room. There, the coliving bedrooms. And up there, the apartments."
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-10 sm:px-16 lg:px-24 mt-4 mb-8">
      <div class="aspect-[4/3] bg-[#E8E3D8] flex items-center justify-center border border-black/5 rounded-sm" role="img" aria-label="Photo to come: first-floor partitions under construction">
